# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: rotating-calipers
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:rotating-calipers/antipodal-point] In mathematics, two points of a sphere (or n-sphere, including a circle) are called **antipodal** or **diametrically opposite** if they are the endpoints of a diameter, a straight line segment between two points on a sphere and passing through its center.
[src:rotating-calipers/antipodal-point] Given any point on a sphere, its antipodal point is the unique point at greatest distance, whether measured intrinsically (great-circle distance on the surface of the sphere) or extrinsically (chordal distance through the sphere's interior).
[src:rotating-calipers/antipodal-point] Every great circle on a sphere passing through a point also passes through its antipodal point, and there are infinitely many great circles passing through a pair of antipodal points (unlike the situation for any non-antipodal pair of points, which have a unique great circle passing through both).
[src:rotating-calipers/antipodal-point] Many results in spherical geometry depend on choosing non-antipodal points, and degenerate if antipodal points are allowed; for example, a spherical triangle degenerates to an underspecified lune if two of the vertices are antipodal.
[src:rotating-calipers/antipodal-point] The point antipodal to a given point is called its **antipodes**, from the Greek ἀντίποδες (*antípodes*) meaning "opposite feet"; see Antipodes § Etymology.
[src:rotating-calipers/antipodal-point] Sometimes the *s* is dropped, and this is rendered **antipode**, a back-formation.
[src:rotating-calipers/antipodal-point] The concept of *antipodal points* is generalized to spheres of any dimension: two points on the sphere are antipodal if they are opposite *through the centre*.
[src:rotating-calipers/antipodal-point] Each line through the centre intersects the sphere in two points, one for each ray emanating from the centre, and these two points are antipodal.
[src:rotating-calipers/antipodal-point] The Borsuk–Ulam theorem is a result from algebraic topology dealing with such pairs of points.
[src:rotating-calipers/antipodal-point] It says that any continuous function from $S^{n}$ to $\mathbb {R} ^{n}$ maps some pair of antipodal points in $S^{n}$ to the same point in $\mathbb {R} ^{n}.$ Here, $S^{n}$ denotes the n -dimensional sphere and $\mathbb {R} ^{n}$ is n -dimensional real coordinate space.
[src:rotating-calipers/antipodal-point] The **antipodal map** $A:S^{n}\to S^{n}$ sends every point on the sphere to its antipodal point.
[src:rotating-calipers/antipodal-point] If antipodal points are identified (considered equivalent), the sphere becomes a model of real projective space.
[src:rotating-calipers/convex-polygon] In geometry, a **convex polygon** is a polygon that is the boundary of a convex set.
[src:rotating-calipers/convex-polygon] This means that the line segment between two points of the polygon is contained in the union of the interior and the boundary of the polygon.
[src:rotating-calipers/convex-polygon] In particular, it is a simple polygon (not self-intersecting).
[src:rotating-calipers/convex-polygon] Equivalently, a polygon is convex if every line that does not contain any edge intersects the polygon in at most two points.
[src:rotating-calipers/convex-polygon] A convex polygon is *strictly* convex if no line contains more than two vertices of the polygon.
[src:rotating-calipers/convex-polygon] In a convex polygon, all interior angles are less than *or equal* to 180 degrees, while in a strictly convex polygon all interior angles are strictly less than 180 degrees.
[src:rotating-calipers/convex-polygon] Every polygon inscribed in a circle (such that all vertices of the polygon touch the circle), if not self-intersecting, is convex.
[src:rotating-calipers/convex-polygon] However, not every convex polygon can be inscribed in a circle.
[src:rotating-calipers/convex-polygon] Every non-degenerate triangle is strictly convex.
[src:rotating-calipers/diameter-computational-geometry] In computational geometry, the diameter of a finite set of points or of a polygon is its diameter as a set, the largest distance between any two points.
[src:rotating-calipers/diameter-computational-geometry] The diameter is always attained by two points of the convex hull of the input.
[src:rotating-calipers/diameter-computational-geometry] A trivial brute-force search can be used to find the diameter of n points in time $O(n^{2})$ (assuming constant-time distance evaluations) but faster algorithms are possible for points in low dimensions.
[src:rotating-calipers/diameter-computational-geometry] In two dimensions, the diameter can be obtained by computing the convex hull and then applying the method of rotating calipers.
[src:rotating-calipers/diameter-computational-geometry] The diameter is the maximum distance between any pair of convex hull vertices found as the two points of contact of the parallel lines in this sweep.
[src:rotating-calipers/diameter-computational-geometry] The time for this method is dominated by the time for constructing the convex hull: $O(n\log n)$ for a finite set of n points, or time $O(n)$ for a simple polygon with n vertices.
[src:rotating-calipers/diameter-computational-geometry] For a dynamic two-dimensional point set subject to point insertions and deletions, an approximation to the diameter, with an approximation ratio that can be chosen arbitrarily close to one, can be maintained in time $O(\log ^{2}n)$ per operation.
[src:rotating-calipers/diameter-computational-geometry] In three dimensions, the diameter of a set of points can again be computed in time $O(n\log n)$ .
[src:rotating-calipers/diameter-computational-geometry] A randomized method for doing this by Clarkson and Shor uses as a subroutine a randomized incremental algorithm for finding the intersection of congruent spheres.
[src:rotating-calipers/diameter-computational-geometry] The algorithm repeatedly chooses a random input point, finds the farthest distance $\rho$ from it, intersects spheres with radius $\rho$ centered at each point, and eliminates the points contained in the resulting intersection.
[src:rotating-calipers/diameter-computational-geometry] The eliminated points are within distance $\rho$ of all other points, and therefore cannot be part of any pair with a larger distance than $\rho$ .
[src:rotating-calipers/diameter-computational-geometry] Each point is eliminated when the farthest distance from it is less than or equal to $\rho$ , the farthest distance from the randomly chosen point, which happens with probability ${\tfrac {1}{2}}$ , so half of the points are eliminated in expectation in each iteration of the algorithm.
[src:rotating-calipers/diameter-computational-geometry] The total expected time for the algorithm is dominated by the time to find the first intersection of spheres, before the problem is simplified by eliminating any points.
[src:rotating-calipers/diameter-computational-geometry] Ramos provides a non-random algorithm by using ε-nets to derandomize a variation of the Clarkson and Shor algorithm, with the same asymptotic runtime.
[src:rotating-calipers/diameter-computational-geometry] In any fixed dimension d , there exists an algorithm for which the exponent of n in the time bound is less than two.
[src:rotating-calipers/diameter-computational-geometry] It is also possible to approximate the diameter, to within a $(1+\varepsilon )$ approximation ratio, in time $O(n+\varepsilon ^{1/2-d})$ .
[src:rotating-calipers/minimum-bounding-box] When other kinds of measure are used, the minimum box is usually called accordingly, e.g., "minimum-perimeter bounding box".
[src:rotating-calipers/minimum-bounding-box] The minimum bounding box of a point set is the same as the minimum bounding box of its convex hull, a fact which may be used heuristically to speed up computation.
[src:rotating-calipers/minimum-bounding-box] In the two-dimensional case it is called the *minimum bounding rectangle*.
[src:rotating-calipers/minimum-bounding-box] The axis-aligned minimum bounding box (or **AABB**) for a given point set is its minimum bounding box subject to the constraint that the edges of the box are parallel to the (Cartesian) coordinate axes.
[src:rotating-calipers/minimum-bounding-box] It is the Cartesian product of *N* intervals each of which is defined by the minimal and maximal value of the corresponding coordinate for the points in *S*.
[src:rotating-calipers/minimum-bounding-box] Axis-aligned minimal bounding boxes are used as an approximate location of an object in question and as a very simple descriptor of its shape.
[src:rotating-calipers/minimum-bounding-box] For example, in computational geometry and its applications when it is required to find intersections in the set of objects, the initial check is the intersections between their MBBs.
[src:rotating-calipers/minimum-bounding-box] Since it is usually a much less expensive operation than the check of the actual intersection (because it only requires comparisons of coordinates), it allows quickly excluding checks of the pairs that are far apart.
[src:rotating-calipers/minimum-bounding-box] The arbitrarily oriented minimum bounding box is the minimum bounding box, calculated subject to no constraints as to the orientation of the result.
[src:rotating-calipers/minimum-bounding-box] A three-dimensional rotating calipers algorithm can find the minimum-volume arbitrarily-oriented bounding box of a three-dimensional point set in cubic time.
[src:rotating-calipers/minimum-bounding-box] Matlab implementations of the latter as well as the optimal compromise between accuracy and CPU time are available.
[src:rotating-calipers/minimum-bounding-box] In the case where an object has its own local coordinate system, it can be useful to store a bounding box relative to these axes, which requires no transformation as the object's own transformation changes.
[src:rotating-calipers/minimum-bounding-box] In digital image processing, the *bounding box* is merely the coordinates of the rectangular border that fully encloses a digital image when it is placed over a page, a canvas, a screen or other similar bidimensional background.
[src:rotating-calipers/rotating-calipers] In computational geometry, the method of **rotating calipers** is an algorithm design technique that can be used to solve optimization problems including finding the width or diameter of a set of points.
[src:rotating-calipers/rotating-calipers] The method is so named because the idea is analogous to rotating a spring-loaded vernier caliper around the outside of a convex polygon.
[src:rotating-calipers/rotating-calipers] Every time one blade of the caliper lies flat against an edge of the polygon, it forms an antipodal pair with the point or edge touching the opposite blade.
[src:rotating-calipers/rotating-calipers] The complete "rotation" of the caliper around the polygon detects all antipodal pairs; the set of all pairs, viewed as a graph, forms a thrackle.
[src:rotating-calipers/rotating-calipers] The method of rotating calipers can be interpreted as the projective dual of a sweep line algorithm in which the sweep is across slopes of lines rather than across x- or y-coordinates of points.
[src:rotating-calipers/rotating-calipers] The rotating calipers method was first used in the dissertation of Michael Shamos in 1978.
[src:rotating-calipers/rotating-calipers] Shamos used this method to generate all antipodal pairs of points on a convex polygon and to compute the diameter of a convex polygon in $O(n)$ time.
[src:rotating-calipers/rotating-calipers] Godfried Toussaint coined the phrase "rotating calipers" and demonstrated that the method was applicable in solving many other computational geometry problems.
